<subSubSection id="C32E54C8163DFFD2B59EE60F6828C893" pageId="43" pageNumber="359" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8B0743163DFFD2B59EE60F6A2EC83E" blockId="43.[160,1156,1320,1519]" box="[160,375,1320,1346]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis id="B940DB51163DFFD2B59EE60F6A2EC83E" bold="true" box="[160,375,1320,1346]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">Geographic range</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B0743163DFFD2B59EE66B6828C893" blockId="43.[160,1156,1320,1519]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">
This species is a successful invasive and is considered cosmopolitan. 
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC0163DFFD2B6C8E66B6A4EC8FB" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetramorium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simillimum">
<emphasis id="B940DB51163DFFD2B6C8E66B6A4EC8FB" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">Tetramorium simillimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is of African origin (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB2163DFFD2B734E64869CFC8FB" author="Bolton B" box="[522,662,1391,1415]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359" pagination="67 - 151" refId="ref17772" refString="Bolton B. 1977. The ant tribe Tetramoriini (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). The genus Tetramorium Mayr in the Oriental and Indo-Australian regions, and in Australia. Bull Br Museum (Nat Hist) Entomol. 36: 67 - 151." type="journal article" year="1977">Bolton 1977</bibRefCitation>
) with a broad distribution in the 
<collectingRegion id="49F0C9A1163DFFD2B11AE6486FD9C8FB" box="[1060,1152,1391,1415]" country="Saudi Arabia" name="Ash Sharqiyah" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">Oriental</collectingRegion>
, Indo-Australian, Australian, Neotropical (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB2163DFFD2B748E6B5685CC8D6" author="Kempf WW" box="[630,773,1426,1450]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359" pagination="3 - 344" refId="ref19494" refString="Kempf WW. 1972. Catalogo abreviado das formigas da regiao Neotropical. Studia Entomologica. 15: 3 - 344." type="journal article" year="1972">Kempf 1972</bibRefCitation>
), Nearctic (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB2163DFFD2B6B0E6B56F1DC8D6" author="Creighton WS" box="[910,1092,1426,1450]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359" pagination="1 - 585" refId="ref18310" refString="Creighton WS. 1950. The ants of North America. Bull Museum Comp Zool. 104: 1 - 585." type="journal article" year="1950">Creighton 1950</bibRefCitation>
) and Polynesian (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB2163DFFD2B417E6936963C8B0" author="Wilson EO &amp; Taylor RW" box="[297,570,1460,1484]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359" pagination="1 - 109" refId="ref21421" refString="Wilson EO, Taylor RW. 1967. The ants of Polynesia (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Pac Insects Monogr. 14: 1 - 109." type="journal article" year="1967">Wilson and Taylor 1967</bibRefCitation>
) regions. From the Arabian Peninsula, it has been recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D3163DFFD2B472E6F06A21C893" box="[332,376,1495,1519]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">KSA</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D3163DFFD2B48AE6F0695BC893" box="[436,514,1495,1519]" name="Yemen" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">Yemen</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB2163DFFD2B72FE6F0683CC893" author="Collingwood CA &amp; Agosti D" box="[529,869,1495,1519]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359" pagination="300 - 385" refId="ref18173" refString="Collingwood CA, Agosti D. 1996. Formicidae (Insecta: Hymenoptera) of Saudi Arabia (part 2). Fauna of Saudi Arabia. 15: 300 - 385." type="journal article" year="1996">Collingwood and Agosti 1996</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32E54C8163DFFD2B59EE53C68AECB06" pageId="43" pageNumber="359" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B8B0743163DFFD2B59EE53C694CCB49" blockId="43.[160,1156,1563,1658]" box="[160,533,1563,1589]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis id="B940DB51163DFFD2B59EE53C694CCB49" bold="true" box="[160,533,1563,1589]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">Ecological and biological notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B0743163DFFD2B59EE51868AECB06" blockId="43.[160,1156,1563,1658]" pageId="43" pageNumber="359">Workers of this species were found foraging on the soil under thrown, dry, date palm fronds. Several workers were found foraging on the ground under grasses.</paragraph>
